\subsection{Demotion}
We define an operation $\dash^\ominus$ which takes a wide context to a narrow context.
Demotion turns normal variables into weak variables and leaves other variables alone.


\[
\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ (\wid\Gamma, x : \wid A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\wid\Gamma^\ominus, x \div \erase{\wid A})$\\
 $ (\wid\Gamma, x :: \wid A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\wid\Gamma^\ominus, x :: \wid A)$\\
 $ (\wid\Gamma, x \div \nar A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\wid\Gamma^\ominus, x \div \nar A)$\\
 $ (\cdot)^\ominus$&$:=$&$\cdot$\\
\end{tabular}\]


\subsection{Semantics}
We imagine the target language of our `semantics' to be ordinary dependent type theory
with no exotic contexts or types or terms.
We define operations $\dash^*$ and $\sem\dash$ and $\tsem\dash\dash$ so that syntactically:

\begin{tabular}{l}
If $\wid \Gamma$ is a wide context, then ${\wid \Gamma}^*$ is a context.\\
If $\wid A$ is a wide type, then ${\wid A}^*$ is a type.\\
If $\wid M$ is a wide term, then ${\wid M}^*$ is a term.
If $\wid \Gamma$ is a wide context, then $\sem{\wid \Gamma}$ is a context.\\
If $\wid A$ is a wid type and $M$ is a term, then $\tsem {\wid A} {M}$ is a type.\\
If $\wid M$ is a wide term, then $\sem{\wid M}$ is a term.\\
If $\nar \Gamma$ is a narrow context, then ${\nar \Gamma}^*$ is a context.\\
If $\nar A$ is a narrow type, then ${\nar A}^*$ is a type.\\
If $\nar M$ is a narrow term, then ${\nar M}^*$ is a term.
\end{tabular}

Furthermore we wish to prove that these operations preserve typing:

\begin{tabular}{l}
If $\prov {\wid\Gamma}\rctx$, then $\prov {{\wid\Gamma}}^*\rctx$.\\
If ${\wid\Gamma} \prov {\wid A} : \rtype$, then ${\wid\Gamma}^* \prov {\wid A}^* : \rtype$.\\
If ${\wid\Gamma} \prov {\wid M} : {\wid A}$, then ${\wid\Gamma}^* \prov {\wid M}^* : {{\wid A}}^*$.\\
If $\prov {\wid\Gamma}\rctx$, then $\prov \sem{{\wid\Gamma}}\rctx$.\\
If ${\wid\Gamma} \prov {\wid A} : \rtype$, then $\sem {\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid {\wid A}^* \prov \tsem {\wid A} x : \rtype$.\\
If ${\wid\Gamma} \prov {\wid M} : {\wid A}$, then $\sem{\wid\Gamma} \prov \sem {\wid M} : \tsem {\wid A} {\wid M^*}$\\
If $\prov {\nar\Gamma}\rctx$, then $\prov {{\nar\Gamma}}^*\rctx$.\\
If ${\nar\Gamma} \prov {\nar A} : \rtype$, then ${\nar\Gamma}^* \prov {\nar A}^* : \rtype$.\\
If ${\nar\Gamma} \prov {\nar M} : {\nar A}$, then ${\nar\Gamma}^* \prov {\nar M}^* : {{\nar A}}^*$.\\
\end{tabular}
\subsection{Rules}

\subsubsection{Context Formation}
These are the rules for well-formed contexts. The type of a strong variable
is typed in the demotion of the context to its left. The type of a weak variable
is typed in the context to its left augmented with a $\star$.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\justifies
\prov \cdot \rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\justifies
\prov \emptyset \rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x : \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma, \star \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, \star )\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]

Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
(\Gamma, x : \wid A)^* &=& (\Gamma^*, x^* : A^*)\\
(\Gamma, x :: \wid A)^* &=& (\Gamma^*, x^* : A^*, \sem x : \tsem A {M^*})\\
(\Gamma, x \div \nar A)^* &=& (\Gamma^*, x^* : A^*)\\
(\Gamma, \star)^* &=& \Gamma^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\sem{\Gamma, x : \wid A} &=& (\sem\Gamma, x^* : A^*, \sem x : \tsem A {M^*})\\
\sem{\Gamma, x :: \wid A} &=& (\sem\Gamma, x^* : A^*, \sem x : \tsem A {M^*})\\
\sem{\Gamma, x \div \nar A} &=& (\sem\Gamma, x^* : A^*)\\
\sem{\Gamma, \star} &=& \alpha : 0\\
\end{array}\]
\subsubsection{Variable Rules}
We can use strong or ordinary variables whenever they are in the context.
Weak variables require that a $\star$ is present in the context for them to be used;
$\star$ acts like a key that unlocks them. Weak variables are essentially the locked
part of the context in the sense of MTT.

One might reasonably ask why it is that strong and ordinary variables appear to behave identically here;
the answer is that the difference between them lies in how they respond to demotion. Strong variables
remain strong after demotion, but ordinary variables do not.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
x : \wid A \in  \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : \wid A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x :: \wid A \in  \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : \wid A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x \div \nar A \in  \Gamma \qquad \star \in \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : \wid A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\subsection{New Operations}
\par \noindent $\Gamma^Z$ takes an $\Gamma$ and produces an $\nar \Gamma$
\par \noindent $A^Z$ takes an $A$ and produces an $\nar A$
\par \noindent $M^Z$ takes an $M$ and produces an $\nar M$
\par \noindent $\nar \Gamma^\ominus$ takes a $\nar \Gamma$ and produces a $\Gamma$
\par \noindent $ \Gamma^\oplus$ takes a $ \Gamma$ and produces a $\nar \Gamma$
\par \noindent If $\bprov \nar \Gamma  \rctx$ then $\prov \nar \Gamma^\ominus \rctx$
\par \noindent If $\nar \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype$ then $\nar \Gamma \bprov A^Z : \rtype$
\par \noindent $\Gamma = \nar\Gamma ^\ominus$
\par \noindent $(\Gamma^Z)^* = \Gamma^*, (A^Z)^* = A^*, (M^Z)^* = M^*$
\par \noindent $(\nar \Gamma^\ominus)^* = \nar \Gamma^*$
\par \noindent $\sem {\nar \Gamma^\ominus} = \nar \Gamma^*$
\par \noindent $( \Gamma^\oplus)^* = \sem \Gamma$

\subsection{Type Formers}


\subsubsection{The Fiber Type}
The type $\pp M A$ represents the `fiber over $M$ in the map in the arrow category' or
`the proofs that $M$ belongs to the logical relation'
or `the proofs that $M$ is a good, special, nice, parametric element of the type $A$'.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nar \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \quad \nar \Gamma \bprov \nar M : A^Z
\justifies
\nar \Gamma \bprov \pp {\nar M} A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\quad
\begin{prooftree}
{\nar \Gamma}^\ominus \prov M : A
\justifies
\nar \Gamma \prov \{M\} : \pp {M^Z} A
\end{prooftree}
\quad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^Z \bprov \nar M : A^Z \quad \Gamma^\oplus \bprov \nar N : \pp {\nar M} A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \epair {\nar M} {\nar N} : A
\end{prooftree}
\]

Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{\pp {\nar M} A}^* &=& \tsem A {\nar M^*}\\
\{M\}^* &=& \sem M\\
(\epair {\nar M} {\nar N})^* &=& {\nar M}^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\\
\\
\sem{\epair {\nar M}{\nar N}} &=& {\nar N}^*\\
\end{array}\]
\subsubsection{The Open Modality}
The modality $\lax$ can be thought of as the functor from $\rtype^{\bf 2}$ to itself that takes
any function $f : A \to B$ and returns the identity $B \to B$. To apply $\lax$ is to `move to unique the future world'
or `go downstairs' if we think of $A$ lying above $B$, and to forget everything we knew about the upstairs data.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nar \Gamma^J \prov  A : \rtype
\justifies
\nar\Gamma \bprov  \lax A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, \star \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \ilax M  : \lax A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma \prov M : \lax A\qquad \star \in \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \elax M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{(\lax A)}^* &=&  A^*\\
(\ilax M)^* &=& M^*\\
(\elax M)^* &=& M^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\\
\\
\sem{\elax M} &=& \babort(\alpha)\\
\end{array}\]

\subsubsection{The Square Root Modality}
The modality $\surd$ can be thought of as the functor from $\rtype^{\bf 2}$ to itself that takes
any function $f : A \to B$ and returns the identity $A \to A$. To apply $\surd$ is to `retreat to the past world'
or `go upstairs', i.e. replace the data `downstairs' with the points that were formerly available upstairs.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \surd A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \isurd M  : \surd A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, \star \prov M : \surd A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \esurd M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{(\surd A)}^* &=&  (x : \wid A^*) \x \tsem A x\\
(\isurd M)^* &=& \pair {M^*} {\sem M}\\
(\esurd M)^* &=& (M^*).1\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\surd A}\_ &=& 1\\
\sem{\isurd M} &=& \langle\rangle\\
\sem{\esurd M} &=& (M^*).2\\
\end{array}\]

\subsubsection{The Closed Modality}
The modality $\blat$ can be thought of as the functor from $\rtype^{\bf 2}$ to itself that takes
any function $f : A \to B$ and returns the unique map $A \to 1$. To apply $\blat$ is to destroy all distinctions
we formerly made `downstairs', while retaining all `upstairs' data.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov  A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \blat A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \iblat M  : \blat A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : \blat A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \eblat M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{(\blat A)}^* &=& 1\\
(\iblat M)^* &=& \langle\rangle\\
(\eblat M)^* &=& \sem M.1\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\blat A}\_ &=&  (x : \wid A^*) \x \tsem A x\\
\sem{\iblat M} &=& \pair {M^*} {\sem M}\\
\sem{\eblat M} &=& \sem M.2\\
\end{array}\]

\subsubsection{The Glue Type}
The glue type takes specifications of a `downstairs' and `upstairs' type and glues them together.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, \star \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma^\oplus, \star, x : \wid A\prov B : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \gg(x : \wid A) . B : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, \star \prov M : A  \qquad \Gamma^\oplus, \star \prov N : [M/x]B
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \mpair M N : \gg(x : \wid A) . B : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma \prov  M : \gg(x : \wid A) . B
\justifies
\Gamma, \star \prov M.1 : A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma \prov  M : \gg(x : \wid A) . B
\justifies
  \Gamma^\oplus, \star\prov M.2 : [M.1/x]B
\end{prooftree}
\]

Semantics:
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{( \gg(x : \wid A) . B)}^* &=& A^*\\
\mpair M N ^* &=& M^*\\
(M.1)^* &=&  M^*\\
(M.2)^* &=& \sem M\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{ \gg(x : \wid A) . B} {M^*} &=&  [M^*/x^*]B^*\\
\sem{ \mpair M N } &=& N^*\\
\sem{M.1} &=& \babort(\alpha)\\
\sem{M.2} &=& \babort(\alpha)\\
\end{array}\]

\section{Interesting Theorems}

\subsection{The Nondependent Function Type}
If
\[ \prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov B : \rtype \qquad
\Gamma, \star \prov f : A \to B\]
then there exists an explicit isomorphism
\[\Gamma \prov \pp f {A \to B}  \cong (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B \]
Explicitly, here is the construction:
\[ \Gamma \prov \mathsf{fore} : (f' : \pp f {A \to B}) (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B \]
\[\mathsf{fore} = \lambda f'.\lambda a.\lambda a'.  \{(\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'})\}\]
\[ \Gamma \prov \mathsf{back} : (k : (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B) \to \pp f {A \to B} \]
\[\mathsf{back} = \lambda k. \{\lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}})\}\]
Let's typecheck these. Make some abbreviations
\[\Gamma_1 = (\Gamma^\ominus, f' \div \pp f {A \to B}, a \div  A, a' \div \pp { a} A) \]
\[\Gamma_2 = ( \Gamma^\ominus, k \div (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B)\]
\[\Gamma_3 = (\Gamma_2, x :: \wid A, \star)\]
and see
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov f  :  A \to B
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov f' :  \pp f {A \to B}
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_1 \prov \epair f {f'} :  A \to B
\]
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov { a}  :  A
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_1, \star \prov a' :  \pp { a} A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_1 \prov \epair { a} {a'} :  A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_1 \prov (\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'}) :  B
\]
\justifies
\Gamma, f' : \pp f {A \to B}, a :  A, a' : \pp { a} A \prov \{(\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'})\} : \pp {f\ a} B
\end{prooftree}
\]
checking as a side condition that
\[ (\epair f {f'})\ (\epair { a} {a'})\equiv_\star f\ a\]
and then
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  k : (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  x : \wid A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  {k\ x} : \pp x A \to  \pp {f\ x} B
\]
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  x :  A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  {\{x\}} : \pp x A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_3 \prov  {k\ x\ \{x\}} : \pp {f\ x} B
\end{prooftree}
\]
can be inserted into
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\[
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : \wid A, \star \prov f : A \to B
\]
\[
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : \wid A, \star \prov x : \wid A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : \wid A, \star \prov f\ x : B
\]
\qquad
{\vdots \atop \Gamma_3 \prov  {k\ x\ \{x\}} : \pp {f\ x} B}
\justifies
\Gamma_2, x : \wid A \prov \epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}} : B
\]
\justifies
\Gamma_2 \prov \lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}}) : A \to B
\]
\justifies
\Gamma, k : (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} B) \prov \{\lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}})\} : \pp f {A \to B}
\end{prooftree}
\]
checking as a side condition that
\[ \lambda x . (\epair {f\ x} {k\ x\ \{x\}}) \equiv_\star f\]

\subsection{The Dependent Function Type}
This is very similar to the non-dependent case. The difference is we must substitute into $B$.
If
\[ \prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma^\ominus, x : \wid A \prov B : \rtype \qquad
\Gamma, \star \prov f : (x : \wid A) \to B\]
then there exists an explicit isomorphism
\[\Gamma \prov \pp f {(x : \wid A) \to B}  \cong (a :  A) (a' : \pp { a} A) \to \pp {f\ a} {[\epair a {a'} / x]B} \]

